n, difference, deconstruction, praxis, ethics, responsibility, objectivity, narrative strategy, and situatedness. Including a series of essays, reflections, and interviews marking the trajectory of the author's work as a feminist methodologist, Getting Lost will be an important text for courses in sociology of science, philosophy of science, ethnography, feminist methodology, women and gender studies, and qualitative research in education and related social science fields.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aFeminist theory. 0aSocial sciencesxPhilosophy. 0aSocial sciencesxResearchxPhilosophy. 4aEducation : Education. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aDhunpath, Rubby, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerumal, Juliet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmithies, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791480267423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791480267/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles